[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] The use of Java-related technology in Android led to a legal dispute between Oracle and Google.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 7, 2012, a San Francisco jury found that if APIs could be copyrighted, then Google had infringed Oracle's copyrights by the use of Java in Android devices.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] District Judge William Alsup ruled on May 31, 2012, that APIs cannot be copyrighted, but this was reversed by the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit in May 2014.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] On May 26, 2016, the district court decided in favor of Google, ruling the copyright infringement of the Java API in Android constitutes fair use.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] In March 2018, this ruling was overturned by the Appeals Court, which sent down the case of determining the damages to federal court in San Francisco.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] Google filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the Supreme Court of the United States in January 2019 to challenge the two rulings that were made by the Appeals Court in Oracle's favor.
[src:mockito-java-lib/java-programming-language] On April 5, 2021, the Court ruled 6–2 in Google's favor, that its use of Java APIs should be considered fair use.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] In computer programming, a **mock object** is an object that imitates a production object in limited ways.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] A programmer might use a mock object as a test double for software testing.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] A mock object can also be used in generic programming.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] A mock object can be useful to the software tester like a car designer uses a crash test dummy to simulate a human in a vehicle impact.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] In a unit test, mock objects can simulate the behavior of complex, real objects and are therefore useful when a real object is impractical or impossible to incorporate into a unit test.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] For example, an alarm clock program which causes a bell to ring at a certain time might get the current time from a time service.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] To test this, the test must wait until the alarm time to know whether it has rung the bell correctly.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] If a mock time service is used in place of the real time service, it can be programmed to provide the bell-ringing time (or any other time) regardless of the real time, so that the alarm clock program can be tested in isolation.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Mock objects have the same interface as the real objects they mimic, allowing a client object to remain unaware of whether it is using a real object or a mock object.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Many available mock object frameworks allow the programmer to specify which methods will be invoked on a mock object, in what order, what parameters will be passed to them, and what values will be returned.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Thus, the behavior of a complex object such as a network socket can be mimicked by a mock object, allowing the programmer to discover whether the object being tested responds appropriately to the wide variety of states such mock objects may be in.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The definitions of mock, fake and stub are not consistent across the literature.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Nonetheless, all represent a production object in a testing environment by exposing the same interface.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Regardless of name, the simplest form returns pre-arranged responses (as in a method stub) and the most complex form imitates a production object's complete logic.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Such a test object might contain assertions to examine the context of each call.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] For example, a mock object might assert the order in which its methods are called, or assert consistency of data across method calls.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] In the book *The Art of Unit Testing* mocks are described as a fake object that helps decide whether a test failed or passed by verifying whether an interaction with an object occurred.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] In that book, *fakes* are anything that is not real, which, based on their usage, can be either *stubs* or *mocks*.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Consider an example where an authorization subsystem has been mocked.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The mock object implements an `isUserAllowed(task : Task) : boolean` method to match that in the real authorization class.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Many advantages follow if it also exposes an `isAllowed : boolean` property, which is not present in the real class.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] This allows test code to easily set the expectation that a user will, or will not, be granted permission in the next call and therefore to readily test the behavior of the rest of the system in either case.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Similarly, mock-only settings could ensure that subsequent calls to the sub-system will cause it to throw an exception, hang without responding, or return `null` etc.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Thus, it is possible to develop and test client behaviors for realistic fault conditions in back-end sub-systems, as well as for their expected responses.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Without such a simple and flexible mock system, testing each of these situations may be too laborious for them to be given proper consideration.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] A mock database object's `save(person : Person)` method may not contain much (if any) implementation code.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] It might check the existence and perhaps the validity of the Person object passed in for saving (see fake vs. mock discussion above), but beyond that there might be no other implementation.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The mock method could add an entry to a public log string.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The entry need be no more than "Person saved", or it may include some details from the person object instance, such as a name or ID.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] If the test code also checks the final contents of the log string after various series of operations involving the mock database, then it is possible to verify that in each case exactly the expected number of database saves have been performed.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] This can find otherwise invisible performance-sapping bugs, for example, where a developer, nervous of losing data, has coded repeated calls to `save()` where just one would have sufficed.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Programmers working with the test-driven development (TDD) method make use of mock objects when writing software.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Mock objects meet the interface requirements of, and stand in for, more complex real ones; thus they allow programmers to write and unit-test functionality in one area without calling complex underlying or collaborating classes.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Using mock objects allows developers to focus their tests on the behavior of the system under test without worrying about its dependencies.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] For example, testing a complex algorithm based on multiple objects being in particular states can be clearly expressed using mock objects in place of real objects.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Apart from complexity issues and the benefits gained from this separation of concerns, there are practical speed issues involved.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Developing a realistic piece of software using TDD may easily involve several hundred unit tests.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] If many of these induce communication with databases, web services and other out-of-process or networked systems, then the suite of unit tests will quickly become too slow to be run regularly.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] This in turn leads to bad habits and a reluctance by the developer to maintain the basic tenets of TDD.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] When mock objects are replaced by real ones, the end-to-end functionality will need further testing.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] These will be integration tests rather than unit tests.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The use of mock objects can closely couple the unit tests to the implementation of the code that is being tested.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] This illustrates that unit tests should test a method's external behavior rather than its internal implementation.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Over-use of mock objects as part of a suite of unit tests can result in a dramatic increase in the amount of maintenance that needs to be performed on the tests themselves during system evolution as refactoring takes place.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] The improper maintenance of such tests during evolution could allow bugs to be missed that would otherwise be caught by unit tests that use instances of real classes.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Conversely, simply mocking one method might require far less configuration than setting up an entire real class and therefore reduce maintenance needs.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] Mock objects have to accurately model the behavior of the object they are mocking, which can be difficult to achieve if the object being mocked comes from another developer or project or if it has not even been written yet.
[src:mockito-java-lib/mock-object] If the behavior is not modelled correctly, then the unit tests may register a pass even though a failure would occur at run time under the same conditions that the unit test is exercising, thus rendering the unit test inaccurate.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In computer science, **reflective programming** or **reflection** is the ability of a process to examine, introspect, and modify its own structure and behavior.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] The earliest computers were programmed in their native assembly languages, which were inherently reflective, as these original architectures could be programmed by defining instructions as data and using self-modifying code.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] As the bulk of programming moved to higher-level compiled languages such as ALGOL, COBOL, Fortran, Pascal, and C, this reflective ability largely disappeared until new programming languages with reflection built into their type systems appeared.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Brian Cantwell Smith's 1982 doctoral dissertation introduced the notion of computational reflection in procedural programming languages and the notion of the meta-circular interpreter as a component of 3-Lisp.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection helps programmers make generic software libraries to display data, process different formats of data, perform serialization and deserialization of data for communication, or do bundling and unbundling of data for containers or bursts of communication.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflective systems may provide a mirror type, used as a decoupled reflection of an object or identifier.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Effective use of reflection almost always requires a plan: A design framework, encoding description, object library, a map of a database or entity relations.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection makes a language more suited to network-oriented code.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For example, it assists languages such as Java to operate well in networks by enabling libraries for serialization, bundling and varying data formats.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Languages without reflection such as C are required to use auxiliary compilers for tasks like Abstract Syntax Notation to produce code for serialization and bundling.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be used for observing and modifying program execution at runtime.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A reflection-oriented program component can monitor the execution of an enclosure of code and can modify itself according to a desired goal of that enclosure.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] This is typically accomplished by dynamically assigning program code at runtime.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In object-oriented programming languages such as Java, reflection allows *inspection* of classes, interfaces, fields and methods at runtime without knowing the names of the interfaces, fields, methods at compile time.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] It also allows *instantiation* of new objects and *invocation* of methods.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is often used as part of software testing, such as for the runtime creation/instantiation of mock objects.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection is also a key strategy for metaprogramming.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In some object-oriented programming languages such as C# and Java, reflection can be used to bypass member accessibility rules.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For C#-properties this can be achieved by writing directly onto the (usually invisible) backing field of a non-public property.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] It is also possible to find non-public methods of classes and types and manually invoke them.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] This works for project-internal files as well as external libraries such as .NET's assemblies and Java's archives.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A language that supports reflection provides a number of features available at runtime that would otherwise be difficult to accomplish in a lower-level language.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] These features can be implemented in different ways.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In MOO, reflection forms a natural part of everyday programming idiom.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] When verbs (methods) are called, various variables such as `verb` (the name of the verb being called) and `this` (the object on which the verb is called) are populated to give the context of the call.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Compiled languages rely on their runtime system to provide information about the source code.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A compiled Objective-C executable, for example, records the names of all methods in a block of the executable, providing a table to correspond these with the underlying methods (or selectors for these methods) compiled into the program.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In a compiled language that supports runtime creation of functions, such as Common Lisp, the runtime environment must include a compiler or an interpreter.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection can be implemented for languages without built-in reflection by using a program transformation system to define automated source-code changes.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Reflection may allow a user to create unexpected control flow paths through an application, potentially bypassing security measures.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Historical vulnerabilities in Java caused by unsafe reflection allowed code retrieved from potentially untrusted remote machines to break out of the Java sandbox security mechanism.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] A large scale study of 120 Java vulnerabilities in 2013 concluded that unsafe reflection is the most common vulnerability in Java, though not the most exploited.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Runtime reflection systems introduce a non-negligible runtime performance overhead.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] For instance, in Java, because reflective operations are resolved dynamically at execution time, many compiler and JVM optimizations—such as method inlining, static binding, and aggressive just-in-time specialization—cannot be fully applied.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] As a consequence, reflective calls are typically slower than their statically resolved counterparts.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In sequential applications, reflection can significantly increase execution time and memory consumption when used in performance-critical code paths.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In multithreaded applications, reflective implementations generally preserve scalability, but still exhibit noticeably higher absolute execution times—commonly between 1.5x and 10× slower—than equivalent non-reflective code.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] In languages like C++ and Rust, reflection is performed at compile time.
[src:mockito-java-lib/reflection-computer-programming] Compile-time reflection systems are weaker than runtime reflection systems like those of Java and C#, but incur no runtime overhead due to being performed during compilation.
